node.text:
Repost from @gretathunberg
•
One of my greatest sources of hope lies in the huge potential of rewilding and restoring nature. This, together with climate equity and stop burning fossil fuels, is the key towards a sustainable world. 
Nature now, by Tom Mustill #FaceTheClimateEmergency

node.text:
Repost from @dustinwilsonms
•
If you haven’t watched this yet, do it now. @sippingsocialite from the @thehuesociety shares a very personal and powerful story about her path in the wine industry. I have so much respect for this brave woman. Show her your love and support!  As for the @mastersommeliers_americas, some serious work needs to be done.

node.text: As harvest begins at Domaine de la Côte, I am proud to share with you our 2017 vintage—the culmination of the first decade of our endeavor in the Sta. Rita Hills. Please visit our website at 9 AM PDT on Tuesday, September 3 to acquire these offerings. 🎥 @bimarianfilms

node.title: Domaine de la Côte 2017 Vintage Release—Tuesday, September 3

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Rajat Parr on August 04, 2021 tagging @art_science_cider_wine, and @nate_ready. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and nature.

node.text:
As we are approaching harvest  I wanted to thank these two AMAZING humans who have helped me shape the vintage @phelanfarms so far. Without Dan and Nate I don’t think I would have been able to stay on the path I chose. I was lucky to spend the day with them few weeks ago.
Hope you guys get a chance to experience the delicious wines & cider of @art_science_cider_wine @hiyuwinefarm @florealcider

node.text:
Repost from @yeti
•
Winemakers know better than anyone that patience makes any reward sweeter. Once a year, experts like Rajat Parr eagerly await that pivotal pocket of time when Mother Nature delivers the fruits of her labor. And when the time is ripe, they transform each perfected grape into a taste only achievable through longevity (and a little elbow grease).⁠
⁠
Discover the new Harvest Red Collection through the link in our bio.

I am proud to announce the release of the 10th vintage from @domainedelacote, the 2019 vintage. The vintage was a special one for @sashimoorman and myself, and the wines are equally as special - a delicate balance of fruit, complexity and perfumed aromas that will unveil themselves over the years. ⁠
⁠
View the release at our link in bio.

We had an amazing 2 days seeding the forest garden with Vera (my God Daughter). We planted cider apples & pear (20 different old varieties) 2 months ago. Last weekend we seeded the garden with Medicinal herbs and flowers (for our Sprays and co-fermentation). It’s incredible to see them grow and get the love from Little Vera. She turns 6 this weekend. I can’t wait to watch them them both grow.

The orchard is named “Vera’s Garden” @phelanfarms

node.text: At Evening Land, we designed our Wine Club with members in mind first. Our team envisioned a place where curious drinkers could get to know the land that we love and dive into the wines it produces, as well as create memories around these bottles with friends and loved ones along the way. Our wine community is a special place. It's made up of a diverse group of faces, palate preferences, and backgrounds, all united by a shared love of wine and the memories it fosters. ELV Wine Club has a place for you. We hope you'll join us on this journey. Link in bio for membership details / registration. #elvwineclub

node.text:
I have been working with my friend @scholiumwines on a very special project for a few years: the Los Angeles River Wine Company. I am really excited to announce the second release of wines from this project, just bottled in February.
Since 2019, we have been working together to uncover the remarkable and barely known historical vineyards of Southern California. Before Prohibition, the center of winemaking in California was in Los Angeles-- not Napa or Sonoma. Most of the vineyards from this time were replaced long ago by factories, warehouses, and freeways. But not all. We work with several vineyards that were all planted before Prohibition. The most special we discovered with our friend, @christinarasmussen_ , who flew to Los Angeles from London to work with us on the first harvest. The vineyard was planted in 1912 on a Native American reservation, and was abandoned about 60 years ago. It is planted to a field blend of Mission and Grenache and Zinfandel and who knows what else. She named the vineyard Lone Wolf, because a half-wolf, half-dog that patrols the vineyard and protects the nearby children.
We are in the middle of our second year of caring for the vineyard. The wine that we make from Lone Wolf is fantastic: a light but intense red, like the wines from the Mediterranean. When I tasted it this Spring, right after bottling, I was amazed. It is one of the best wines being made in America right now.
I want to introduce you to all of these wines now, before they disappear. We made only tiny amounts-- 20 cases of some wines. Abe and I have put together a special 6-bottle selection. 
To purchase, LINK in BIO
